ily in this model.Alex Gourlay -- Co-Chief Operating Officer for Walgreens Boots Alliance, Inc., and President, WalgreensAnd just finally, sorry Charles, I missed LabCorp. LabCorp are a really important partners to us. We have about 110, 112, I think, as exactly, so that really continues. And we're developing of course, new models with them for testing. And obviously, we'll continue to work very closely with our team. So again, we feel very good about our partnership with LabCorp.Charles Rhyee -- Cowen and Company -- AnalystGreat, thank you.OperatorAnd our next question comes from the line of Kevin Caliendo from UBS. Your line is open.Kevin Caliendo -- UBS -- AnalystThank you. Thanks for taking my call. I just wanted to get a little bit more detail on the impact, the delta between your online sales and your inside store sales, sort of, what they were, what's the difference in gross margin on that, and what are your expectations going forward? Is this the new normal or do you expect foot traffic to increase and online sales to stay where they are? I'd love to sort of get a take on the impact now and what you expect the mix to be going forward?James Kehoe -- Executive Vice President and Global Chief Financial OfficerYes, I'll take a bit of a shot at that. Our biggest online business is actually in the U.K., and it's $500 million plus business and has a very strong position in beauty. And what we're looking at right now and you know I said in the prepared remarks, foot traffic in our stores was down 85%, which was a tremendous impact in the U.K. So, effectively it was at a standstill. And at the beginning of the crisis, we didn't have enough capacity in our online business and we've exited the quarter with sufficient capacity for the future.So, what are we seeing right now? We are seeing in the U.K. that there is a slow recovery on the high street, our transactions are still down 46%. Again, it's a huge number. But our online business over the last weeks and months is 