ich I think is an advantage in the long-term. But at the moment, they are urban areas that are most affected by the risk and the fear of the pandemic.So, for example, in New York City and Manhattan, we have almost a 100 stores in Manhattan alone, and you can imagine the footfall and the sales and the transactions are heavily down in these markets.Stefano Pessina -- Executive Vice Chairman and Chief Executive OfficerYes, it's quite interesting, because as Alex said, it's very geographically dispersed. So, we have -- a large proportion of our stores are rural and they were up about 8% in the quarter. And you've got a small number of urban stores, maybe 300 to 400 urban stores, and they were down 18%. So, as you move out of the big cities, which have been disproportionately impacted, our performance is much-much better.Kevin Caliendo -- UBS -- AnalystThank you so much.Alex Gourlay -- Co-Chief Operating Officer for Walgreens Boots Alliance, Inc., and President, WalgreensThank you.OperatorOur next question comes from the line of Steven Valiquette from Barclays. Your line is open.Steven Valiquette -- Barclays -- AnalystGreat, thanks. Good morning, everyone. So, my question actually, kind of, picks up wherever you left off, on some of the geographic discussion in the U.S. I'm not sure if you're able to comment on this or not. But some investors are wondering whether you're seeing any dichotomy in the most recent trends in Sunbelt states like Florida and Texas versus trends in the upper Midwest and Northeast, where things are more stable now? To separate from their rural versus urban, I think just people are focused on the Sunbelt. Just any comments you can make geographically, given some of the investor concerns around rising COVID cases in some key states might also be helpful. Thanks.Alex Gourlay -- Co-Chief Operating Officer for Walgreens Boots Alliance, Inc., and President, WalgreensThanks, Steve. It's Alex here. The reality is there are hotspots where we're seeing som